NORMALISED EXTRACT — DIRECT IMPLEMENTATION CONTENT

1. UUID (RFC 4122 / RFC 9562)
- Internal representation: 16 octets (128 bits) encoded in network byte order (most significant byte first).
- Field layout (octet offsets):
  time_low: unsigned 32-bit integer at octets 0..3
  time_mid: unsigned 16-bit integer at octets 4..5
  time_hi_and_version: unsigned 16-bit integer at octets 6..7 (high 4 bits = version)
  clock_seq_hi_and_reserved: unsigned 8-bit at octet 8 (high bits contain variant)
  clock_seq_low: unsigned 8-bit at octet 9
  node: unsigned 48-bit at octets 10..15
- Variant field: resides in the most significant bits of octet 8 (clock_seq_hi_and_reserved). For the RFC 4122 variant (variant 1) set top two bits to 10 (binary). Other patterns reserved.
- Version field: high 4 bits of time_hi_and_version. Standard versions defined include:
  1: time-based (timestamp + node)
  2: DCE Security (POSIX domain-specific)
  3: name-based MD5
  4: randomly or pseudo-randomly generated
  5: name-based SHA-1
  6: reordered time-based (timestamp bits reordered to be lexicographically sortable)
  7: timestamp + random (48-bit epoch ms + version + sub-ms/monotonic bits + variant + remainder)

2. UUID Algorithms (concrete steps)
- Version 1 (time-based) generation steps:
  1. Obtain a 60-bit timestamp as number of 100-nanosecond intervals since 00:00:00.00, 15 October 1582 UTC.
  2. If multiple UUIDs generated within the same timestamp, increment a clock sequence low-order mechanism; maintain or randomize a 13-14 bit clock sequence when system clock moves backwards or node id changes.
  3. Compose fields: time_low (low 32 bits of timestamp), time_mid (next 16 bits), time_hi_and_version (high 12 bits of timestamp OR'ed with version in high 4 bits).
  4. Node: prefer IEEE 802 MAC address (48 bits). If not available or for privacy, use random 48-bit node and set multicast bit (least-significant bit of first octet) to 1 to indicate non-MAC node.
  5. Set variant bits in clock_seq_hi_and_reserved to RFC pattern (10x). Clock sequence occupies 14 bits across clock_seq_hi_and_reserved and clock_seq_low.

- Version 3 / 5 (name-based) generation steps:
  1. Convert namespace UUID to 16-byte network-order representation.
  2. Convert name to UTF-8 bytes.
  3. Concatenate namespace bytes with name bytes.
  4. Compute hash: MD5 for v3 (128-bit digest), SHA-1 for v5 (160-bit digest).
  5. Take first 16 bytes of digest (for v5 truncate SHA-1). Overwrite the time_hi_and_version high 4 bits with version number and set variant bits in clock_seq_hi_and_reserved to RFC pattern.

- Version 4 (random) generation steps:
  1. Generate 16 random bytes (128 bits) from a cryptographically secure RNG.
  2. Set version: time_hi_and_version = (time_hi_and_version & 0x0FFF) | (4 << 12).
  3. Set variant: clock_seq_hi_and_reserved = (clock_seq_hi_and_reserved & 0x3F) | 0x80 (i.e., set top two bits to 10).

- Version 7 (timestamp + random/monotonic) construction (RFC 9562 / community spec):
  1. 48-bit big-endian unsigned Unix epoch milliseconds (ms since 1970-01-01) into the most significant bits.
  2. Set 4-bit version field to 7.
  3. Provide 12 bits for sub-ms precision/monotonic counter or pseudorandom value.
  4. Set variant bits to 10.
  5. Fill remaining 62 bits with pseudorandom or monotonic data as implementation chooses.

3. UUID Bit-Level Operations (exact masks and ops)
- Set version (generic): time_hi_and_version = (time_hi_and_version & 0x0FFF) | (version << 12)
  - Example (v4): time_hi_and_version = (time_hi_and_version & 0x0FFF) | 0x4000
- Set variant to RFC 4122 (binary 10x in top bits of octet 8):
  clock_seq_hi_and_reserved = (clock_seq_hi_and_reserved & 0x3F) | 0x80
  Explanation: &0x3F clears top two bits; |0x80 sets bit pattern 10xxxxxx.
- Clock sequence composition:
  clock_seq = 14-bit value; clock_seq_hi_and_reserved high 6 bits store upper 6 bits of clock_seq plus variant high bits; clock_seq_low holds low 8 bits.
- Byte ordering: when serializing string representation, print fields as zero-padded hexadecimal with network byte order applied per the field table.

4. Base64 (RFC 4648)
- Alphabet (RFC 4648 base64): index 0..63 maps to "A..Z a..z 0..9 + /" (explicit mapping per RFC).
- Encoding grouping: take input bytes in 3-byte groups -> 24 bits -> split into four 6-bit groups -> map to 4 characters.
- Padding: if input length mod 3 = 1 produce two output chars + '=='; if mod 3 = 2 produce three output chars + '='. Padding character '=' indicates how many bytes were padded.
- URL-safe variant (base64url): replace '+' with '-' and '/' with '_' and optionally omit padding '=' for URL contexts.
- Decoding: discard non-alphabet characters (some variants allow ignoring whitespace). Decoders can infer missing padding from length but behaviour varies; secure implementations should require or validate padding according to chosen profile.

5. Ascii85 / Adobe Ascii85
- Alphabet: encode 32-bit big-endian group into 5 base-85 digits mapped to ASCII by adding 33; allowed printable chars are '!' (33) through 'u' (117). Special-case 'z' encodes 0x00000000 (4 zero bytes) as a single 'z'.
- Grouping: take 4 input bytes => 32-bit big-endian integer N; compute digits d4..d0 by repeated division by 85; output characters (d4+33)...(d0+33).
- Padding: pad final group with 0x00 bytes to 4 bytes before encoding; after encoding, remove as many characters as padding added (Adobe truncation rule). When decoding, pad final 5-tuple with 'u' characters then strip padded output bytes.
- Delimiters (Adobe): optional prefix '<~' and suffix '~>' around Ascii85 payload.
- Note: some characters used have special meaning in XML/SGML; escape when embedding in these contexts.

6. Base62
- Alphabet used commonly: 0-9, A-Z, a-z (value mapping 0..61). Explicit canonical ordering: '0'..'9' => values 0..9, 'A'..'Z' => 10..35, 'a'..'z' => 36..61. Implementations vary; confirm alphabet before interoperating.
- Encoding approach: convert binary value to big integer then repeatedly divide by 62 producing digits; leading zeros handling depends on chosen canonicalization.

7. base-x (cryptocoinjs) API and behaviour
- Constructor: basex(alphabet: string) -> encoder object.
- Encoder object methods:
  encode(buffer: Uint8Array | Buffer) -> string  (encodes bytes to alphabet string)
  decode(string: string) -> Uint8Array  (decodes alphabet string to bytes)
- Leading-zero handling: base-x preserves leading zero bytes by encoding each leading zero as the alphabet first character (bitcoin-style leading-zero compression). This means encoded length is variable but leading zeros are recoverable on decode.
- Warning: base-x is NOT RFC 3548 compliant for base16/base32/base64; use only for arbitrary alphabets (base58, base62 etc.).

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS — TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS AND IMPLEMENTATION NOTES

UUID specifics and canonical string representation
- Canonical textual form: 36-character lowercase hex with hyphens separating fields: 8-4-4-4-12, e.g. f81d4fae-7dec-11d0-a765-00a0c91e6bf6
- When converting between binary and text forms, ensure network byte order for multi-octet fields and exact zero-padding of hex digits.
- Nil UUID: all-zero 16 bytes: 00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000
- Max/Omni UUID: all-ones 16 bytes: FFFFFFFFFFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFF-FFFFFFFFFFFF (useful sentinel)

Name-based UUID exact hash usage
- v3: MD5(namespace || name) -> 128-bit digest; set version=3 and set variant bits; use first 16 bytes verbatim (except version/variant).
- v5: SHA-1(namespace || name) -> 160-bit digest; take leftmost 16 bytes, set version=5, set variant bits.
- Namespace constants used in practice: DNS, URL, OID, X.500; when using, provide their UUID byte representations in network byte order.

Randomness and security
- For v4 and any random-based components (v7 random tail, node randomization for v1), use a cryptographically secure RNG (CSPRNG) where unpredictability matters.
- For privacy when omitting MAC node for v1/v6, set multicast/local bit (least-significant bit of first node octet) to 1 to indicate non-MAC node per RFC.

Base64/Ascii85 encoding performance notes
- Base64: fastest in typical libraries; decoding tolerant of extra whitespace and line breaks in MIME contexts but canonical implementations validate alphabet membership.
- Ascii85: produces ~25% overhead vs base64 ~33% for typical binary lengths; Adobe variant includes delimiters and specific padding/truncation behaviour.

